[30;1m127 | [0m[35m[0m
[30;1m128 | [0m[35m* Construct *nodeids* during collection; each test is assigned[0m
[30;1m129 | [0m[35m  a unique *nodeid* which is rooted at the ``rootdir`` and takes into account[0m
[30;1m130 | [0m[35m  the full path, class name, function name and parametrization (if any).[0m
[30;1m131 | [0m[35m[0m
[30;1m132 | [0m[35m* Is used by plugins as a stable location to store project/test run specific information;[0m

[30;1m43 | [0m[35m[0m
[30;1m44 | [0m[35m**Cleanup** is where the test picks up after itself, so other tests aren't being[0m

[30;1m46 | [0m[35m[0m

[30;1m48 | [0m[35m**arrange** step only providing the context. **Behavior** exists between **act**[0m
[30;1m49 | [0m[35mand **assert**.[0m

[30;1m31 | [0m[35mthe system under test (SUT), and it's the resulting changed state that we can[0m
[30;1m32 | [0m[35mlook at to make a judgement about the behavior. This typically takes the form of[0m
[30;1m33 | [0m[35ma function/method call.[0m
[30;1m34 | [0m[35m[0m
[30;1m35 | [0m[35m**Assert** is where we look at that resulting state and check if it looks how[0m

[30;1m3 | [0m[35mAnatomy of a test[0m
[30;1m4 | [0m[35m=================[0m
[30;1m5 | [0m[35m[0m
[30;1m6 | [0m[35mIn the simplest terms, a test is meant to look at the result of a particular[0m
[30;1m7 | [0m[35mbehavior, and make sure that result aligns with what you would expect.[0m
[30;1m8 | [0m[35mBehavior is not something that can be empirically measured, which is why writing[0m
[30;1m9 | [0m[35mtests can be challenging.[0m

[30;1m22 | [0m[35mline options while the environment is in use:[0m

[30;1m169 | [0m[35m[0m
[30;1m170 | [0m[35mBy default ``group_contains()`` will recursively search for a matching[0m
[30;1m171 | [0m[35mexception at any level of nested ``ExceptionGroup`` instances. You can[0m
[30;1m172 | [0m[35mspecify a ``depth`` keyword parameter if you only want to match an[0m
[30;1m173 | [0m[35mexception at a specific level; exceptions contained directly in the top[0m
[30;1m174 | [0m[35m``ExceptionGroup`` would match ``depth=1``.[0m

[30;1m422 | [0m[35m~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~[0m
[30;1m423 | [0m[35m[0m
[30;1m424 | [0m[35m``pytest`` rewrites test modules on import by using an import[0m
[30;1m425 | [0m[35mhook to write new ``pyc`` files. Most of the time this works transparently.[0m
[30;1m426 | [0m[35mHowever, if you are working with the import machinery yourself, the import hook may[0m
[30;1m427 | [0m[35minterfere.[0m
[30;1m428 | [0m[35m[0m

[30;1m556 | [0m[35m[0m
[30;1m557 | [0m[35m.. code-block:: bash[0m
[30;1m558 | [0m[35m[0m

[30;1m560 | [0m[35m[0m
[30;1m561 | [0m[35mand look at the content at the ``path`` location.  Such files are used e.g.[0m

[31m--[ [0m[34mMatch #[0m[33m342[0m[34m of [0m[33m2330[0m[31m ]--[0m
   Rule Id: [34mBD000610[0m

[30;1m341 | [0m[35m[0m
[30;1m342 | [0m[35m* Each test inside the file gets its own line in the output.[0m
[30;1m343 | [0m[35m* ``test_words_fail`` gives the same output as before in this case.[0m
[30;1m344 | [0m[35m* ``test_numbers_fail`` now shows a full text diff of the two dictionaries.[0m

[30;1m346 | [0m[35m  text at all, regardless of its size.[0m
[30;1m347 | [0m[35m[0m

[30;1m190 | [0m[35mfuncargs/fixture discovery now happens at collection time[0m
[30;1m191 | [0m[35m---------------------------------------------------------------------[0m
[30;1m192 | [0m[35m[0m
[30;1m193 | [0m[35mSince pytest-2.3, discovery of fixture/funcarg factories are taken care of[0m
[30;1m194 | [0m[35mat collection time.  This is more efficient especially for large test suites.[0m
[30;1m195 | [0m[35mMoreover, a call to "pytest --collect-only" should be able to in the future[0m
[30;1m196 | [0m[35mshow a lot of setup-information and thus presents a nice method to get an[0m
[30;1m197 | [0m[35moverview of fixture management in your project.[0m

[30;1m47 | [0m[35m- simplified and fixed implementation for calling finalizers when[0m
[30;1m48 | [0m[35m  parametrized fixtures or function arguments are involved.  finalization[0m
[30;1m49 | [0m[35m  is now performed lazily at setup time instead of in the "teardown phase".[0m
[30;1m50 | [0m[35m  While this might sound odd at first, it helps to ensure that we are[0m
[30;1m51 | [0m[35m  correctly handling setup/teardown even in complex code.  User-level code[0m
[30;1m52 | [0m[35m  should not be affected unless it's implementing the pytest_runtest_teardown[0m
[30;1m53 | [0m[35m  hook and expecting certain fixture instances are torn down within (very[0m

[30;1m47 | [0m[35m- simplified and fixed implementation for calling finalizers when[0m
[30;1m48 | [0m[35m  parametrized fixtures or function arguments are involved.  finalization[0m
[30;1m49 | [0m[35m  is now performed lazily at setup time instead of in the "teardown phase".[0m
[30;1m50 | [0m[35m  While this might sound odd at first, it helps to ensure that we are[0m
[30;1m51 | [0m[35m  correctly handling setup/teardown even in complex code.  User-level code[0m
[30;1m52 | [0m[35m  should not be affected unless it's implementing the pytest_runtest_teardown[0m

[30;1m16 | [0m[35m[0m
[30;1m17 | [0m[35mAn **xfail** means that you expect a test to fail for some reason.[0m
[30;1m18 | [0m[35mA common example is a test for a feature not yet implemented, or a bug not yet fixed.[0m
[30;1m19 | [0m[35mWhen a test passes despite being expected to fail (marked with ``pytest.mark.xfail``),[0m
[30;1m20 | [0m[35mit's an **xpass** and will be reported in the test summary.[0m

[30;1m151 | [0m[35m.. note::[0m
[30;1m152 | [0m[35m[0m
[30;1m153 | [0m[35m    Node IDs are of the form ``module.py::class::method`` or[0m
[30;1m154 | [0m[35m    ``module.py::function``.  Node IDs control which tests are[0m
[30;1m155 | [0m[35m    collected, so ``module.py::class`` will select all test methods[0m
[30;1m156 | [0m[35m    on the class.  Nodes are also created for each parameter of a[0m
[30;1m157 | [0m[35m    parametrized fixture or test, so selecting a parametrized test[0m

[30;1m328 | [0m[35mmypy frown upon this, and it may also cause conflicts with other plugins.[0m
[30;1m329 | [0m[35mSo pytest offers a better way to do this, :attr:`item.stash <_pytest.nodes.Node.stash>`.[0m
[30;1m330 | [0m[35m[0m
[30;1m331 | [0m[35mTo use the "stash" in your plugins, first create "stash keys" somewhere at the[0m
[30;1m332 | [0m[35mtop level of your plugin:[0m
[30;1m333 | [0m[35m[0m
[30;1m334 | [0m[35m.. code-block:: python[0m

[31m--[ [0m[34mMatch #[0m[33m1459[0m[34m of [0m[33m2330[0m[31m ]--[0m
   Rule Id: [34mBD000600[0m
       Tag: [34mSecurity.Backdoor.LOLBAS.Windows[0m
  Severity: [36mModerate[0m, Confidence: [36mLow[0m
  Filename: [33m/pytest-8.3.5/doc/en/how-to/writing_hook_functions.rst[0m
   Pattern: [32m\s(advpack\.dll|appvlp|at|atbroker|bash|bginfo|bitsadmin|cdb|certutil|cl_invocation\.ps1|cl_mutexverifiers\.ps1|cmd|cmdkey|cmstp|comsvcs\.dll|control|csc|cscript|csi|devtoolslauncher|dfsvc|diskshadow|dnscmd|dnx|dotnet|dxcap|esentutl|eventvwr|excel|expand|extexport|extrac32|findstr|forfiles|ftp|gfxdownloadwrapper|gpscript|hh|ie4uinit|ieadvpack\.dll|ieaframe\.dll|ic|infdefaultinstall|installutil|jsc|makecab|manage-bde\.wsf|mavinject|mftrace|microsoft\.workflow\.compiler|mmc|msbuild|msconfig|msdeploy|msdt|mshta|mshtml\.dll|msc|msxsl|netsh|odbcconf|pcalua|pcwrun|pcwutl\.dll|pester\.bat|powerpnt|presentationhost|pubprn\.vbs|rcsi|reg|regasm|regedit|register-cimprovider|regsvcs|regsvr32|rpcping|rundll32|runonce|runscripthelper|sc|schtasks|scriptrunner|setupapi\.dll|shdocvw\.dll|shell32\.dll|slmgr\.vbs|sqldumper|sqlps|sqltoolsps|squirrel|syncappvpublishingserver|syncappvpublishingserver\.vbs|syssetup\.dll|te|tracker|tttracer|update|url\.dll|verclsid|vsjitdebugger|wab|winrm\.vbs|winword|wmic|wscript|wsl|wsreset|xwizard|zipfldr\.dll)\s[0m
[30;1m222 | [0m[35m.. note::[0m
[30;1m223 | [0m[35m    Hooks receive parameters using only keyword arguments.[0m
[30;1m224 | [0m[35m[0m
[30;1m225 | [0m[35mNow your hook is ready to be used. To register a function at the hook, other plugins or users must[0m
[30;1m226 | [0m[35mnow simply define the function ``pytest_my_hook`` with the correct signature in their ``conftest.py`[0m
[30;1m227 | [0m[35m[0m
[30;1m228 | [0m[35mExample:[0m

[31m--[ [0m[34mMatch #[0m[33m1460[0m[34m of [0m[33m2330[0m[31m ]--[0m
   Rule Id: [34mBD000600[0m
       Tag: [34mSecurity.Backdoor.LOLBAS.Windows[0m
  Severity: [36mModerate[0m, Confidence: [36mLow[0m
  Filename: [33m/pytest-8.3.5/doc/en/how-to/writing_hook_functions.rst[0m
   Pattern: [32m\s(advpack\.dll|appvlp|at|atbroker|bash|bginfo|bitsadmin|cdb|certutil|cl_invocation\.ps1|cl_mutexverifiers\.ps1|cmd|cmdkey|cmstp|comsvcs\.dll|control|csc|cscript|csi|devtoolslauncher|dfsvc|diskshadow|dnscmd|dnx|dotnet|dxcap|esentutl|eventvwr|excel|expand|extexport|extrac32|findstr|forfiles|ftp|gfxdownloadwrapper|gpscript|hh|ie4uinit|ieadvpack\.dll|ieaframe\.dll|ic|infdefaultinstall|installutil|jsc|makecab|manage-bde\.wsf|mavinject|mftrace|microsoft\.workflow\.compiler|mmc|msbuild|msconfig|msdeploy|msdt|mshta|mshtml\.dll|msc|msxsl|netsh|odbcconf|pcalua|pcwrun|pcwutl\.dll|pester\.bat|powerpnt|presentationhost|pubprn\.vbs|rcsi|reg|regasm|regedit|register-cimprovider|regsvcs|regsvr32|rpcping|rundll32|runonce|runscripthelper|sc|schtasks|scriptrunner|setupapi\.dll|shdocvw\.dll|shell32\.dll|slmgr\.vbs|sqldumper|sqlps|sqltoolsps|squirrel|syncappvpublishingserver|syncappvpublishingserver\.vbs|syssetup\.dll|te|tracker|tttracer|update|url\.dll|verclsid|vsjitdebugger|wab|winrm\.vbs|winword|wmic|wscript|wsl|wsreset|xwizard|zipfldr\.dll)\s[0m
[30;1m63 | [0m[35mof other hook implementations.  A hook wrapper is a generator function[0m
[30;1m64 | [0m[35mwhich yields exactly once. When pytest invokes hooks it first executes[0m
[30;1m65 | [0m[35mhook wrappers and passes the same arguments as to the regular hooks.[0m
[30;1m66 | [0m[35m[0m
[30;1m67 | [0m[35mAt the yield point of the hook wrapper pytest will execute the next hook[0m
[30;1m68 | [0m[35mimplementations and return their result to the yield point, or will[0m
[30;1m69 | [0m[35mpropagate an exception if they raised.[0m
[30;1m70 | [0m[35m[0m

[31m--[ [0m[34mMatch #[0m[33m1461[0m[34m of [0m[33m2330[0m[31m ]--[0m
   Rule Id: [34mBD000600[0m
       Tag: [34mSecurity.Backdoor.LOLBAS.Windows[0m

[30;1m826 | [0m[35m[0m
[30;1m827 | [0m[35mThe fixture system of pytest is *very* powerful, but it's still being run by a[0m
[30;1m828 | [0m[35mcomputer, so it isn't able to figure out how to safely teardown everything we[0m
[30;1m829 | [0m[35mthrow at it. If we aren't careful, an error in the wrong spot might leave stuff[0m
[30;1m830 | [0m[35mfrom our tests behind, and that can cause further issues pretty quickly.[0m

[30;1m13 | [0m[35mAt a basic level, test functions request fixtures they require by declaring[0m
[30;1m14 | [0m[35mthem as arguments.[0m
[30;1m15 | [0m[35m[0m
[30;1m16 | [0m[35mWhen pytest goes to run a test, it looks at the parameters in that test[0m
[30;1m17 | [0m[35mfunction's signature, and then searches for fixtures that have the same names as[0m
[30;1m18 | [0m[35mthose parameters. Once pytest finds them, it runs those fixtures, captures what[0m
[30;1m19 | [0m[35mthey returned (if anything), and passes those objects into the test function as[0m

[31m--[ [0m[34mMatch #[0m[33m1697[0m[34m of [0m[33m2330[0m[31m ]--[0m
   Rule Id: [34mBD000600[0m
